photo.caption: หินแกะสลัก

ranking_subcategory: #15 of 86 things to do in Da Nang
subcategory_ranking: #15 of 86 things to do in Da Nang
ranking: #15 of 86 things to do in Da Nang
description:
The Da Nang Museum of Cham Sculpture is one of the first museums built in Vietnam by the French. The main building was constructed in 1915. It evokes some motifs of French colonial architecture in the early twentieth century and resembles the image of the Champa temples - towers in Central Viet Nam. 
Visitors will have the opportunity to contemplate more than 400 artifacts on display, including National Treasures and others representing the masterpieces of Champa sculpture in ten centuries (from 5th to 15th). The artifacts were made in a variety of materials, such as sandstone, terracotta, and metal. Grounded in various themes from fertility symbols, deities, mythical animals and architectural decoration from the Hindu and Buddhist, they express the features of cultural and religious values of the Champa people over many generations. 
The Da Nang Museum of Cham Sculpture is a must-see destination for visitors wishing to discover the culture and heritage of Central Viet Nam.
address: No 2, 2 Thang 9 Street, Da Nang Vietnam

description: Da Nang Fine Arts Museum was founded on July 29, 2014 as a representative of the Central Region and Highlands to preserve, introduce and promote the values of the artistic heritage in the area. Located in the center of Da Nang City, at 78 Le Duan Street, Thach Thang Ward, Hai Chau District, Da Nang Fine Arts Museum is currently preserving and displaying a collection of about 1000 works of modern arts and traditional handicrafts in a three-floor exhibition with a total area of 1,185.5 m2. On the first floor, there is a reception, a theme exhibition area and an arts learning space for children. On the second floor, you can see a permanent exhibition that showcases modern art works which cover a wide range of materials, media such as oil, lacquer, silk, graphics and sculptures and so forth. On the third floor, it features a display of traditional folk arts and handicraft artifacts of Da Nang and the Central Region and Highlands as well.
